text:
He hung on Calvary begging for mercy. That was a man. When He hung on Calvary begging for mercy, that was a man. But on Easter morning, when the Angel of the Lord rolled the stone away, and He come up, He proved He was God. No wonder the poet said:
Living, He loved me; dying, He saved me;
Buried, He carried my sins far away;
Rising, He justified freely forever;
Someday He's coming---oh, glorious day!
Sure He was. He was a God-man. He was divine. He was virgin born. God, Jehovah, God overshadowed a little virgin and brought forth the virgin-born Son of God. And that was a tabernacle---or, the dwelling place---of Jehovah Himself. Jehovah walked in a tabernacle of flesh, and paid the price for sin. Don't you never let Him be a prophet. He was the God of the prophets. Sure was. He was more than a good man. He was the God of the good men.

text_no:
Han hang på Golgata og bønnfalte om nåde. Det var en mann. Når Han hang på Golgata og bønnfalte om nåde, var han en mann. Men på påskemorgen, da Herrens Engel rullet vekk steinen og Han sto opp, beviste Han at Han var Gud. Ikke rart poeten sa:
Levende, Elsket Han meg; døende, frelste Han meg;
Begravet, bar Han mine synder langt bort;
Oppstanden, rettferdiggjorde Han fritt for alltid;
En dag kommer Han igjen---å, herlige dag!
Selvfølgelig var Han det. Han var en Gud-mann. Han var guddommelig. Han var jomfrufødt. Gud, Jehova, overskygget en ung jomfru og frembrakte den jomfrufødte Guds Sønn. Og det var en bolig---eller, et bosted---for Jehova Selv. Jehova vandret i et tabernakel av kjøtt og blod og betalte syndens pris. Ikke la Ham bare være en profet. Han var profetenes Gud. Selvfølgelig var Han det. Han var mer enn en god mann. Han var de gode menns Gud.
